column1: Extreme Water Level (EWL) probability dataset(s) for the report "Global and Regional Sea Level Rise Scenarios for the United States: Updated Mean Projections and Extreme Water Level Probabilities Along U.S. Coastlines"

Sweet, W.V., B.D. Hamlington, R.E. Kopp, C.P. Weaver, P.L. Barnard, D. Bekaert, W. Brooks, M. Craghan, G. Dusek, T. Frederikse, G. Garner, A.S. Genz, J.P. Krasting, E. Larour, D. Marcy, J.J. Marra, J. Obeysekera, M. Osler, M. Pendleton, D. Roman, L. Schmied, W. Veatch, K.D. White, and C. Zuzak, 2022:

Global and Regional Sea Level Rise Scenarios for the United States: Updated Mean Projections and Extreme Water Level Probabilities Along U.S. Coastlines. NOAA Technical Report NOS 01. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, National Ocean Service, Silver Spring, MD, 111 pp.
Notes on values for both the 'grids' and 'gauge' locations:

1) Values at the tide gauges are in meters and relative to MHHW on the tidal epoch listed (e.g., 1983-2001 centered on the 1992 midpoint) for the 'local index (u)' but all values are shown adjusted to year 2000 levels using the 'u trend' value.

2) The 'u trend' value is the slope inherent to the hourly data for this location.  For tide gauges with <20 years, a regional trend (as defined by regions in Figure A2.4 and A2.5 in the report) is shown in bold.
3) The 1-degree gridded values are unitless values since the regional sets of data used to form the probabilities all have been normalized (divided by) their respective 'u values'.
4)  To obtain a specific value at a location like a tide gauge, multiply the gridded value by the local index and then add the local index value:
--> Local EWL= (gridded EWL x local index) + local index.  The result will be in meters and MHHW for the epoch of the local index .
5) CI_Low and CI_High are the 2.5% and 97.5% confidence levels whose spread represent the 95% confidence interval
6) The grid lat/long represent the midpoint of a 1-degree grid, e.g., 17.5 and -67.5 represents a 1-dgree grid that spans 17 to 18 degrees lat and -67 to -68 degrees long
7)  Values are labled as return levels (RL) associated with a particular return period (e.g., 0.1, 1 or 10 years [yr]) though referred to as average event frequencies (1/return period) in the report.
